## What this project actually required

This is the part that does not show up in a headline metric. The 0–30 Day model in particular required a level of cross-functional orchestration that I want to be honest about, because it is where most of the real PM work happened.

**Cross-functional coordination across multiple teams:**
Getting a real-time model into a live agent workflow requires alignment between data science, ML engineering, call centre operations, the loyalty and retention team, the platform team owning the agent desktop, compliance, and the business stakeholders defining the offer rules. Each team had different priorities, different timelines, and different definitions of "done." My job was to hold all of those dependencies in a single coherent roadmap and keep every team moving in the same direction.

**Extensive testing infrastructure:**
Real-time in-call models cannot be tested the way batch models are. You cannot just run holdout groups and wait. The model had to be tested in conditions that replicated live agent interactions — which meant building test scenarios, defining what a good score looked like, what a bad score looked like, and what the failure modes were before any real customer call was affected.

**I acted as an agent tester.**
At one point during testing I put myself in the seat of an actual call centre agent — going through the workflow exactly as an agent would, experiencing what the offer pop-up looked like, how quickly it appeared, whether the timing was right, and whether the information surfaced was actionable or confusing. This was one of the most valuable things I did on this project. No amount of spec documents or stakeholder reviews replaces the experience of using the product in the role it was designed for. I came out of that session with a list of UX and timing changes that would not have surfaced any other way.

---

## Validation framework

- **1–30 Day model:** Controlled holdout group A/B experimentation comparing offer-triggered vs. no-intervention cohorts. This let us make a causal claim about the model's impact on attrition rather than a correlational one — important when defending a $6M business case to senior leadership.
- **0–30 Day model:** Live testing with defined scoring thresholds, offer trigger validation, and agent feedback loops built into the testing process.

**Result:** 15% reduction in customer attrition in the treatment group, validated across both models.

